news.title: Shriram Properties' net profit rises 17.93% Q1 FY26
news.para: Shriram Properties announced a 17.93% rise in net consolidated profit, reaching ₹20.59 crore in Q1 FY26, alongside a 24.01% increase in total income to ₹261.54 crore. The company achieved sales of 0.8 million sq ft, valued at ₹441 crore, marking a 17% year-on-year growth.

news.title: Nila Spaces invests ₹5 crore in Earth Fund
news.para: Nila Spaces has invested ₹5 crore in Earth Fund, gaining priority access to innovative ventures in smart infrastructure and digital construction. This strategic move allows Nila Spaces to integrate cutting-edge solutions into its projects. The investment platform supports startups focused on PropTech and climate-friendly real estate advancements.

news.title: Ahmedabad civic body to issue SOP for ready mix concrete plants soon
news.para: The Ahmedabad Municipal Corporation (AMC) is set to release a new standard operating procedure (SOP) for ready mix concrete (RMC) plants, mandating registration and authorization before construction. This action follows AUDA's SOP release in April 2025.

news.title: Karnataka cracks down on illegal layouts, officials face action
news.para: Investigations have revealed that in several instances, officials colluded with landowners to bypass conversion norms, allowing large-scale violations. Revenue Department targets misuse of 11E maps, vowing land seizures, disciplinary measures, and weekly progress checks to curb rampant violations.

news.title: Property owners slam Bengaluru’s civic officials for issuing penalties but not updating e-khata
news.para: BBMP's move to penalize e-khata holders for under-declared parking space, while refusing to update property dimensions even after penalty payment, has sparked outrage among Bengaluru property owners. Residents fear this discrepancy will create disputes within apartment complexes regarding maintenance charges and parking slot ownership.

news.title: Tamil Nadu plans special purpose vehicle for co-working space project
news.para: Chennai is planning more co-working spaces. The state government will create a special purpose vehicle. This SPV will manage these spaces independently. It will ensure smooth functioning. The CMDA plans to host recruitment agencies in these spaces. This will help members find jobs. A portal with job data will also be created. The placement system will be free.

news.title: Gurugram: Over 1,000 notices served over unauthorised commercial activities in residential colonies
news.para: Gurugram's DTCP is intensifying its crackdown on illegal constructions and misuse of stilt parking areas in licensed colonies, contributing to the city's parking crisis. Notices have been issued to property owners in areas like DLF and Sushant Lok for converting parking spaces into unauthorized structures or using residential properties for commercial purposes.

news.title: Consumer forum asks Ghaziabad development body to register flat booked 36 years ago
news.para: The District Consumer Disputes Redressal Commission (DCDRC) has ordered the Ghaziabad Development Authority (GDA) to register a residential property booked 36 years ago by Kunti Yadav. Despite Yadav taking possession in 1994 and completing payments by 1992, GDA refused registration due to alleged pending dues. The DCDRC directed GDA to cancel demand notes and pay compensation for mental distress.

news.title: Thiruvananthapuram: Technopark park invites EOI for second building under QUAD project
news.para: Technopark has invited expressions of interest from qualified IT co-developers for the construction and operation of its second IT building under the QUAD project at Technocity. The project aims to create a live-work-play campus with shopping and residential facilities. The selected developer will lease approximately 4.

news.title: Lucknow development body denies map approval for houses in illegal colonies
news.para: The Lucknow Development Authority (LDA) has decided against approving building maps for houses in 241 illegal colonies with 7.5-meter-wide roads, even with potential mapping norm relaxations. This decision, aligned with the Master Plan 2021, requires such roads to be government-funded and at least 200 meters long for approval.

news.title: Andaman administration to implement apartment ownership regulation soon: Official
news.para: The Andaman and Nicobar Islands administration is finalizing a regulation to allow individual registration of apartments and flats, benefiting residents. The new regulation, expected in 2025, aims to streamline ownership and registration processes, addressing the current issue where buildings with fewer than eight apartments face difficulties in registration and securing bank loans.

news.title: Grovy India posts profit of ₹1.1 crore in Q1 FY26
news.para: Grovy India Ltd, a Delhi-based real estate firm, has reported a net profit of Rs 1.1 crore for the first quarter of this fiscal year, a significant turnaround from the Rs 25 lakh loss in the same period last year. The company's total revenue surged to Rs 8.

news.title: Awfis Space Solutions posts net profit of ₹8.94 crore in Q1 FY26
news.para: Awfis Space Solutions announced a net profit of ₹8.94 crore for the first quarter of fiscal year 2026. The company's total income reached ₹351.54 crore. Revenue grew by 30% year-on-year. Operating EBITDA margin increased significantly. Awfis is also venturing into the office furniture industry with an investment of ₹8–10 crore. The company's tier-II city presence has expanded by approximately 25%.

news.title: RIICO sells undeveloped land at cheaper rates to attract investors in Rajasthan
news.para: RIICO's recent order allows investors to purchase undeveloped industrial land at reduced rates, based on the basic cost and development charges, departing from transparent auctions. This move aims to attract investment to less popular industrial areas and monetize idle land. While industry welcomes cheaper land, concerns arise regarding the allotment process's potential subjectivity, suggesting auctions for fairness.

news.title: ZS leases 50,000 sq ft new office in Hyderabad
news.para: ZS, a global consulting firm, has inaugurated a new office in Hyderabad. This expansion aims to enhance its services for healthcare and life sciences Global Capability Centres in India. The facility, located in HITEC City, can accommodate up to 600 employees. This move is part of ZS's strategy to boost innovation and provide tailored solutions for its global partners.

news.title: JSW Cement's IPO fully subscribed on third day of bids
news.para: JSW Cement's IPO saw full subscription on its third day. Investors are optimistic about the company's growth. Government infrastructure and housing initiatives are key drivers. Cement demand is expected to rise significantly. JSW Cement aims for a valuation of around $2.3 billion. The company will list on exchanges in August. Proceeds will fund a new factory in Rajasthan.

news.title: Goa: CAG flags gaps in welfare system for construction workers, laxity in safety checks
news.para: A CAG performance audit revealed significant shortcomings in Goa's implementation of welfare measures for construction workers. The audit exposed non-registration of migrant laborers, poor data sharing between agencies, and inadequate workplace safety inspections. Despite Supreme Court directives, the Goa Building and Other Construction Workers Welfare Board failed to take timely action, prompting CAG recommendations for improved tracking, awareness, and enforcement.

news.title: Month-long Pimpri Chinchwad civic body's drive demolishes 187 illegal structures
news.para: Pimpri Chinchwad Municipal Corporation has demolished 187 unauthorized structures, encompassing 3.35 lakh sq ft, since July 9 as part of a city-wide anti-encroachment drive. The initiative targeted under-construction sites initially to prevent illegal construction, later expanding to include kiosks and tin sheds. Officials warned of action against negligent ward officials, urging residents to voluntarily remove unauthorized structures.

news.title: Karimadom Colony rehabilitation project gets green light
news.para: Residents of Karimadom Colony may finally see progress. A rehabilitation project stalled since 2023 has received approval. The project aims to house 105 families. Each unit will cost Rs 21 lakh. Construction will be handled by Costford. Work is expected to begin soon and finish within a year. Residents have faced inadequate compensation and unmet promises for years.
